BT 0 g /F2 20 Tf 176.4 720 Td (Chapter 2: Cloud Detectives) Tj ET
q 0.5 G 1 w 72 710 m 540 710 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 680 Td (Sunny lay on the grass and looked up at the clouds floating by.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 664 Td ('Every cloud tells a story about what weather is coming!' she said to her friend.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 648 Td (Some clouds were big and puffy like cotton balls. Others were thin and wispy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 632 Td ('That flat, dark one means rain is probably coming,' Sunny predicted.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 616 Td (Sure enough, twenty minutes later, the rain began to fall!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 600 Td ('How did you know that?' her friend asked, amazed. 'Science!' Sunny grinned.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 13 Tf 72 564 Td (THE SCIENCE: TYPES OF CLOUDS) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 544 Td (Cumulus: Big, puffy, flat-bottomed clouds that look like cotton balls. Usually fair weather.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 528 Td (Stratus: Low, flat, gray blanket clouds that cover the whole sky. Light rain or drizzle.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 512 Td (Cirrus: Thin, wispy, feathery clouds very high up. Made of ice crystals.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 496 Td (Cumulonimbus: Giant tower clouds that bring thunderstorms, heavy rain, and hail!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 480 Td (Clouds form when warm air rises, cools, and water vapor condenses into droplets.) Tj ET
q 0.92 g 67 390 478 89 re f Q
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 77 449 Td (SCIENCE FACT BOX) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 429 Td (* Clouds float because the tiny water droplets are spread over a huge area.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 411 Td (* The highest clouds \(noctilucent\) form 50 miles up - you can see them at night!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 393 Td (* Cloud names come from Latin: cumulus=heap, stratus=layer, cirrus=curl.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 360 Td (TRY THIS!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 344 Td (Keep a cloud journal for a week. Draw the clouds you see and note what weather follows!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 324 Td (THINK ABOUT IT:) Tj ET
BT 0.2 g /F4 10 Tf 82 308 Td (Can you predict tomorrow's weather by looking at today's clouds?) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
